[[Category:Theorems in algebraic geometry]]

In algebraic geometry, the '''Ramanujam–Samuel theorem''' gives conditions for a [[Divisor (algebraic geometry)|divisor]] of a [[local ring]] to be principal.

It was introduced independently by {{harvs|txt|last=Samuel|authorlink=Pierre Samuel|year=1962}} in answer to a question of [[Alexander Grothendieck|Grothendieck]] and by [[C. P. Ramanujam]] in an appendix to a paper by {{harvs|txt|last=Seshadri|year=1963}}, and was generalized by {{harvs|txt|last=Grothendieck|year=1967|loc=Theorem 21.14.1}}.

==Statement==

Grothendieck's version of the Ramanujam–Samuel theorem {{harv|Grothendieck|1967|loc=theorem 21.14.1}} is as follows.
Suppose that ''A'' is a local [[Noetherian ring]] with [[maximal ideal]] ''m'', whose [[Completion (ring theory)|completion]] is [[Integral domain|integral]] and [[Integrally closed domain|integrally closed]], and ρ is a local [[Ring homomorphism|homomorphism]] from ''A'' to a local Noetherian ring ''B'' of larger [[Krull dimension|dimension]] such that ''B'' is [[formally smooth]] over ''A'' and the [[residue field]] of ''B'' is [[Finitely-generated module|finite over]] that of ''A''. Then a [[Algebraic cycle|cycle]] of [[codimension]] 1 in [[Spectrum of a ring|Spec]](''B'') that is principal at the point ''mB'' is principal.

