In [[algebraic geometry]] and [[number theory]], the '''torsion conjecture''' or '''uniform boundedness conjecture''' for [[abelian varieties]] states that the [[order (group theory)|order]] of the [[torsion group]] of an abelian variety over a [[number field]] can be bounded in terms of the dimension of the variety and the number field. A stronger version of the conjecture is that the torsion is bounded in terms of the dimension of the variety and the degree of the number field.

==Elliptic curves==
The (strong) torsion conjecture was first posed by [[Andrew Ogg]] in 1973<ref>{{cite journal|last=Ogg |first=Andrew |authorlink=Andrew Ogg |title=Rational points on certain elliptic modular curves|journal=Proc. Symp. Pure Math. |volume=24 |pages=221-231 |year=1973}}</ref> has been completely resolved in the case of [[elliptic curves]]. [[Barry Mazur]]{{harvs|year=1977|year2=1978|txt=yes}} proved uniform boundedness for elliptic curves over the rationals. His techniques were generalized by {{harvtxt|Kamienny|1992}} and {{harvtxt|Kamienny|Mazur|1995}}, who obtained uniform boundedness for [[quadratic field]]s and number fields of degree at most 8 respectively. Finally, [[Loïc Merel]] ({{harvtxt|1996}}) proved the conjecture for elliptic curves over any number field. The proof centers around a careful study of the rational points on [[classical modular curve]]s. An effective bound for the size of the torsion group in terms of the degree of the number field was given by {{harvtxt|Parent|1999}}.

Mazur provided a complete list of possible torsion subgroups for rational elliptic curves. If ''C''<sub>''n''</sub> denotes the [[cyclic group]] of order ''n'', then the possible torsion subgroups are ''C''<sub>''n''</sub> with 1 ≤ ''n'' ≤ 10, and also ''C''<sub>12</sub>; and the [[Direct sum of groups|direct sum]] of ''C''<sub>2</sub> with ''C''<sub>2</sub>, ''C''<sub>4</sub>, ''C''<sub>6</sub> or ''C''<sub>8</sub>. In the opposite direction, all these torsion structures occur infinitely often over '''Q''', since the corresponding modular curves are all genus zero curves with a rational point. A complete list of possible torsion groups is also available for elliptic curves over quadratic number fields, and there are substantial partial results for cubic and quartic number fields {{harv|Sutherland|2012}}.

